    <title>This $89 Wi-Fi router is designed to let you run whatever firmware you want </title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/zLd6au78rM72gBiru5kh8-QTlzU=/0x84:2000x1417/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73760618/OpenWrt_One_front.0.png" /&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="1zkzR9"&gt;The Software Freedom Conservancy (SFC) &lt;a href="https://sfconservancy.org/news/2024/nov/29/openwrt-one-wireless-router-now-ships-black-friday/"&gt;announced last week&lt;/a&gt; that the OpenWrt One, a Wi-Fi router created with open-source software in mind, is &lt;a href="https://go.redirectingat.com?id=66960X1514734&amp;amp;xs=1&amp;amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.aliexpress.us%2Fitem%2F3256807609464530.html&amp;amp;referrer=theverge.com&amp;amp;sref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theverge.com%2F2024%2F12%2F2%2F24310967%2Fopenwrt-one-wi-fi-router-available-price-software-freedom-conservancy" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"&gt;now available to buy&lt;/a&gt; for $89 on AliExpress. The SFC says the router “will never be locked down” and gives its owners the “right to change, modify, and repair” as they like.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="OpbIKJ"&gt;The OpenWrt One is aimed at giving owners a “hacker-friendly device” that doesn’t rely on private companies’ update schedules and won’t lose support over time. That the OpenWrt One uses open-source software  — it comes with OpenWRT pre-installed — means, in theory, you can keep it up-to-date for as long as you care to use it. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;figure class="e-image"&gt;
        
